Cherry Street, north side, west from and including Scammel, to and including Gouverneur Streets. The 3-story building shown in the foreground, is No. 390, and adjoining a cleared space at the N.E. corner. Note that the opposite corner (N.W.) is also cleared. The other two buildings shown, Nos. 376-378 are at the N.E. corner of Gouverneur Street.

March 22, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

Cherry Street, at the N.W. corner of Scammel Street. Also shown is a view northward on Scammel Street. This clearance was formed by the demolition of Nos. 380-384 Cherry Street, and Nos. 47-45 Scammel Street.

March 22, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

Scammel Street, north from Cherry, to and including Grand (where it terminates) Streets. Note clearances on either side of the street as a result of the demolition of buildings which formerly stood there.
March 22, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

Cherry Street, east from a point to the east of Scammel Street, viewing towards Corlears Hook Park and the Williamsburg Bridge. The tenement at the right is No. 391-3 and it adjoins the S.E. corner of Scammel Street. To the east of same are buildings housing the Old Dutch Mustard Co. These comprise No's. 395 to 405. The latter is a 4 story structure formerly occupied by the New York City Drug Mill. The vacant lot (formerly No's. 407 to 419 inclusive) has recently been cleared of tenements and is at this date, a parking lot.

April 23, 1939
Views: 1 and 2

P. L. Sperr

Cherry Street, west of Scammel Street. In the foreground is Gouverneur Street with a clearance at the N. E. corner and a small park at the N. W. The latter has recently been added to P. S. No. 31, a corner building, at Gouverneur and Monroe Streets.

Cherry Street, at, adjoining and east of the N.E. corner of Scammel Street. The two former 4-story buildings (Nos. 386-388) that stood on this corner have been demolished. The 3-story building shown, is No. 390.

March 22, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

The same area at a later date and slightly more inclusive. No's 1 and 3 are eastward while No. 2 is opposite. The latter shows the old Provident Warehouse standing preparatory to its demolition. This stage follows immediately as shown in No. 3.

Cherry Street, south side, at Scammel Street. The 1 story garage shown is at the S. E. corner. The tenement adjoining same bears No. 391-3 Cherry Street. At the right margin appears a portion of No. 383, a five story building, that in View 2 is under demolition. This stands at the S. W. corner.

Scammel Street, west side, looking down and across clearing to Cherry and Water Streets.

P. L. Sperr
April 23, 1939

Scammel Street, north from Cherry Street, showing a portion of the extensive demolition necessary for the government sponsored public housing project "Vladeck Houses". Included on this narrow thoroughfare are all the buildings from Cherry to Monroe, to Madison Street's. View 2 details a rear house that formerly stood in the center of the left foreground block. This is the structure appearing above the truck. It was entered from 62 Gouverneur Street.
